info.name: NAS v1.7 Public Version
info.description:
NAS 1.7 is an incremental release for NAS, built during Sprint FY25 - 3. It carries the following changes:

**NAS API:**

Relese Notes:

- Network Authorization
    
    - The Policy Cache in NAS will now be invalidated under two circumstances:
        
        - When a role assignation changes for a client, entries in the cache referring to this client will get deleted.
            
        - When a role, permission, or policy defition changes, the entire cache will get invalidated and its envitres eventually expire and get deleted.
            
- Users API
    
    - Applications may now call GET /users/{userId} with a M2M Sage Id token.
        
        - Applications have access to details from any network user.
            
- Accounts API
    
    - A new endpoint GET /accounts/{id} allows applications using a M2M SageId token to get details on any existing network account.
        
- Maintenance
    
    - Fixed an issue where incosistent policy cache entries caused random unathorized responses from NAS.
        
    - Refactored analytical events publisher to publish events directly to AWS Firehose, which will in turn push them to an S3 bucket that is the source of analytical reporting.
        
        - This means that analytical events will no longer appear in NAS logs.
            
    - Solved an issue where bucket stack was preventing first-attempt deployment of NAS, forcing the team to take manual action.
        
        - From this release on, the team will be able to choose which NAS stacks are built and deployed in a CI/CD pipeline run.

item.description: Ensure that already generate the m2m token in the step one.

When using Access Control Services (ACS) with network roles, ensure that both user and client IDs are properly validated for permission to access various resources in the network.

For user token validation, check the `principal_id` (client ID) of the logged-in user to ensure they have the appropriate access. For M2M token validation, verify the permissions and resource access for the M2M (machine-to-machine) client IDs assigned to each service, based on the roles granted."

This version emphasizes the technical aspects of token validation for both user and M2M contexts.

**Usage Instructions:**

Endpoint: `{NASURL}/principals/{ClientId}/policy-check?Resource=sandbox/network/{resource}&Action={action}`

This endpoint allows policy checks for nearly all available resources and actions. The specific combination of `Resource` and `Action` parameters will depend on the policy being validated. In certain cases, the `accountId` or `datasetId` may be required based on the policy's requirements.

For detailed information about the available policies and their requirements, please refer to the ACS Postman collection or the [Access Control Service (ACS) API documentation](https://developer.sage.com/internal/access-control/reference/rest/)

item.description: Basically All the get endpoint to validate that all the info is right and is creating in the organization services(SXP)sandbox database.

This collection provides access to the Network Platform API endpoints, allowing you to manage data and perform actions within the platform.

**Important Note:** This collection requires two separate tokens for authentication:

- **Principal ID & Email:** This information is obtained through a user login and used to identify the current user.
    
- **Machine-to-Machine (M2M) Token:** This token grants permissions for specific actions, such as creating or modifying data.
    

**Getting Started:**

Use the authorization tap to get the user token from this folder. once obtain the token will be add to headers of the chossen endpoint that need it. (Making possible to run all the folder and check the main endpoints functionality using one run)

1. **User Login (Authorization tap of this Folder):**
    
    - Use the provided login endpoint to obtain your **Principal ID** and **Email**.
        
    - Store these values securely for subsequent requests.
        
2. **M2M Token Generation:**
    
    - Utilize the dedicated endpoint to generate a **M2M Token**.
        
    - This token is crucial for authorized actions within the platform.
        
3. **API Endpoints:**
    
    - The collection offers various endpoints categorized by functionalities:
        
        - **GET Endpoints:** These endpoints allow retrieving data from the platform using your Principal ID and Email.(Check the user token Using the GET endpoint "Run this Step First - SageId login Info")
            
        - **POST Endpoints:** These endpoints enable creating or modifying data, requiring both your Principal ID/Email and the M2M Token for authorization.(Locate in folder 1. Create Accounts and Datasets)
            
4. Endpoints for GET Application clients:
    
    1. Use the dedicated endpoint to generate a M2M token first before use it.(Locate in Client ID Verification)
        
5. Endpoints for GET Account:
    
    1. This endpoint allow retrieving data from the platform using M2M token.
        

**Key Points:**

- Both tokens are essential for full functionality.
    
- The login endpoint provides user identification details.
    
- The M2M token grants authorization for data manipulation.
    
- Separate endpoints cater to GET requests (retrieving data) and POST requests (creating/modifying data).
    

**Benefits of Using This Collection:**

- Streamlined testing and interaction with the Network Platform API.
    
- Clear organization of endpoints based on functionalities.
    
- User-friendly workflow for obtaining and utilizing tokens.
    
- **Please note:** This description assumes the collection includes endpoints for user login, M2M token generation, GET requests for retrieving data, and POST requests for creating/modifying data. You might need to adjust the details based on the specific structure of your collection.
    
- The endpoint /datasets/{{tenantId}}/ledger-service-tenant is fixed with and account that already was hardcode the value in the API of orgservices, in future release is going to be possible to fix the value with an specific kind of user so this is only to check the response and funcionality of the endpoint. It is posible to check this in non productive enviroments but not in production.
    
- Finally the endpoint /datasets/{{DatasetId}}/users is fixed inside the folder Query user for datasets because to have many users and to add this must be done using the organization service endpoints. so is posible to check this in non productive enviroments but not in production.
    

Note: In case of troubles with the collection verify if the token is adding to the headers. an for the cases that is an specific user that is not caching the last token, also contact the NAS team to provide help.
